Use PRIVATE_FUNCTION and PRIVATE_PROCEDURE for internal contract logic:
// PRIVATE_FUNCTION -- read-only helper, NOT callable by other contracts
PRIVATE_FUNCTION(CalculateFee)
{
    output.fee = div(input.amount * FEE_RATE, 10000);  // basis points
}

// PRIVATE_PROCEDURE -- state-modifying helper, NOT callable externally
PRIVATE_PROCEDURE(InternalTransfer)
{
    if (state.balances.get(input.from) < input.amount) return;
    state.balances.set(input.from, state.balances.get(input.from) - input.amount);
    state.balances.set(input.to, state.balances.get(input.to) + input.amount);
}

// Call private helpers from public procedures:
PUBLIC_PROCEDURE(Transfer) {
    InternalTransfer_input iInput;
    InternalTransfer_output iOutput;
    iInput.from = qpi.invocator();
    iInput.to = input.recipient;
    iInput.amount = input.amount;
    // Private procedures called directly (not via qpi)
    CALL(InternalTransfer, iInput, iOutput);
}

QPI has no built-in overflow protection. Use these patterns:

// Saturating add (uint64):
// Returns min(a + b, MAX_UINT64)
if (b > 0 && a > 18446744073709551615ULL - b) {
    // Overflow: cap or reject
    a = 18446744073709551615ULL;
} else {
    a = a + b;
}

// Safe subtract (unsigned):
if (b > a) { return; }  // underflow -- reject
a = a - b;

// Safe multiply (uint64 x uint32 = uint64):
// If result would exceed 2^64: use div() to check first
if (b > 0 && a > div(18446744073709551615ULL, b)) {
    // Would overflow
    return;
}
uint64 product = a * b;

// Division: always use div(a, b) -- returns 0 if b==0
// Modulo: always use mod(a, b) -- returns 0 if b==0
// Never use / or % operators

Shareholder governance pattern using share-weighted voting:
struct GOVERNANCE : public ContractBase {
    struct Proposal {
        uint64 votesFor;
        uint64 votesAgainst;
        uint32 deadline;  // tick
        bit executed;
    };
    Array<Proposal, 16> proposals;
    uint32 proposalCount;

    struct Vote_input { uint32 proposalId; bit support; };
    struct Vote_output {};

    PUBLIC_PROCEDURE(Vote) {
        if (qpi.invocationReward() > 0) qpi.transfer(qpi.invocator(), qpi.invocationReward());
        if (input.proposalId >= state.proposalCount) return;
        if (qpi.tick() > state.proposals.get(input.proposalId).deadline) return;
        // Weight vote by share ownership
        uint64 shares = qpi.numberOfShares(MYTKN, SELF, qpi.invocator(), NULL_ID);
        if (shares == 0) return;
        Proposal p = state.proposals.get(input.proposalId);
        if (input.support) { p.votesFor = p.votesFor + shares; }
        else { p.votesAgainst = p.votesAgainst + shares; }
        state.proposals.set(input.proposalId, p);
    }
};

Collection<T,L> provides a multi-key priority queue view of data:
// Declare: Collection<OrderData, 65536> orders;
// Key type is id (address). Each id can have multiple entries.
// Ordered by priority (sint64) per id

struct OrderData { uint64 amount; uint64 price; uint32 tick; };

// Add entry for an address:
OrderData order;
order.amount = input.amount;
order.price = input.price;
order.tick = qpi.tick();
state.orders.add(qpi.invocator(), order, input.price);  // (key, value, priority)

// Get highest priority entry for an address:
OrderData best = state.orders.get(state.orders.headIndex(qpi.invocator()));

// Remove highest priority entry:
state.orders.remove(state.orders.headIndex(qpi.invocator()));

// Iterate all entries for an address:
uint32 idx = state.orders.headIndex(targetId);
while (idx != NULL_INDEX) {
    OrderData entry = state.orders.get(idx);
    idx = state.orders.nextIndex(idx);
}

// Call cleanup() at END_EPOCH after many removes.
// NULL_INDEX = (uint32)-1 = 4294967295

VULNERABILITY: When Contract A calls Contract B via qpi.invokeProcedure(), Contract B can call back into Contract A before the first call finishes.

Example (VULNERABLE):
PUBLIC_PROCEDURE(Withdraw) {
    uint64 bal = state.balances.get(qpi.invocator());
    if (bal == 0) return;
    qpi.transfer(qpi.invocator(), bal);          // Sends QU
    // POST_INCOMING_TRANSFER on attacker contract fires here
    // Attacker calls Withdraw again before this line:
    state.balances.set(qpi.invocator(), 0);      // balance cleared AFTER transfer
}

Fix -- Checks-Effects-Interactions pattern:
PUBLIC_PROCEDURE(Withdraw) {
    uint64 bal = state.balances.get(qpi.invocator());
    if (bal == 0) return;
    state.balances.set(qpi.invocator(), 0);      // Clear FIRST
    qpi.transfer(qpi.invocator(), bal);           // Transfer LAST
}

General rule: Always update state BEFORE external transfers or calls.

VULNERABILITY: Admin or privileged procedures callable by anyone.

Example (VULNERABLE):
PUBLIC_PROCEDURE(SetFeeRate) {
    state.feeRate = input.newRate;  // Anyone can change fee!
}

Fix -- restrict to contract owner (set in INITIALIZE):
INITIALIZE {
    state.owner = qpi.originator();  // Store deployer address
}

PUBLIC_PROCEDURE(SetFeeRate) {
    if (qpi.invocationReward() > 0) qpi.transfer(qpi.invocator(), qpi.invocationReward());
    if (qpi.invocator() != state.owner) return;  // Access check
    if (input.newRate > MAX_FEE_RATE) return;     // Bounds check
    state.feeRate = input.newRate;
}

// Alternative: restrict to shareholders
uint64 shares = qpi.numberOfShares(MYTKN, SELF, qpi.invocator(), NULL_ID);
if (shares == 0) return;

// Note: qpi.originator() = original tx signer (not affected by cross-contract calls)
// qpi.invocator() = immediate caller (may be a contract in cross-contract scenario)

Pattern for exchange-like order books in QPI:

1) Maker posts offer:
PUBLIC_PROCEDURE(PostOffer) {
    if (qpi.invocationReward() > 0) qpi.transfer(qpi.invocator(), qpi.invocationReward());
    // Store offer keyed by owner with priority = price
    Offer o;
    o.asset = input.asset;
    o.amount = input.amount;
    o.price = input.price;
    o.tick = qpi.tick();
    state.offers.add(qpi.invocator(), o, input.price);
}

2) Taker fills offer:
PUBLIC_PROCEDURE(TakeOffer) {
    uint32 idx = state.offers.headIndex(input.maker);
    if (idx == NULL_INDEX) return;
    Offer o = state.offers.get(idx);
    // Validate amount/price and transfer assets/QU via qpi.transfer* APIs
    state.offers.remove(idx);
}

3) Maker cancels offer:
PUBLIC_PROCEDURE(CancelOffer) {
    uint32 idx = state.offers.headIndex(qpi.invocator());
    if (idx != NULL_INDEX) state.offers.remove(idx);
}

Use cleanup()/cleanupIfNeeded() after heavy removals.

Qubic enforces directional call ordering to avoid cyclic dependency issues.

Rule of thumb:
- A contract may call functions/procedures in contracts with lower (or same, for self) index only.
- Calling higher-index contracts is invalid and can fail verification/execution.

Safe pattern:
if (TARGET_CONTRACT_INDEX > SELF_INDEX) {
    // reject or defer
    return;
}
qpi.callFunction(TARGET_CONTRACT_INDEX, fnInput, fnOutput);

Design guidance:
- Put shared utility/oracle contracts at low indexes.
- Higher-index application contracts should depend downward.
- Avoid circular architecture between sibling contracts.

When building external tooling and transaction payloads, ensure inputSize exactly matches the input struct size.

Why it matters:
- Mismatched sizes can corrupt decoding assumptions.
- May cause rejected calls or unsafe behavior in wrappers.

Frontend/tooling pattern:
const expected = SIZEOF_MY_INPUT;
if (payload.inputSize !== expected) {
  throw new Error('Invalid input size for inputType');
}

Contract-side defensive pattern:
- Keep structs minimal and explicit.
- Do not reuse inputType IDs with incompatible struct layouts over upgrades.
- Version input structs if shape changes are required.

Qubic contracts are effectively immutable once live; schema changes must be planned.

Pattern:
struct MYCONTRACT : public ContractBase {
    uint32 schemaVersion;
    // existing fields...

    INITIALIZE {
        state.schemaVersion = 1;
    }

    PUBLIC_FUNCTION(GetVersion) {
        output.version = state.schemaVersion;
    }
};

Upgrade strategy:
1) Deploy V2 contract with explicit migration procedure.
2) Snapshot/port state via controlled calls.
3) Freeze legacy write paths and mark read-only.

Never silently reinterpret old state layouts.

Logging/emit-style side effects are allowed only in state-mutating execution paths.

Rules:
- PUBLIC_FUNCTION must remain pure/read-only.
- Emit/log in PUBLIC_PROCEDURE or lifecycle hooks where deterministic output is preserved.
- Include stable, fixed-size fields in emitted data for easier decoding.

Pattern:
PUBLIC_PROCEDURE(DoAction) {
    // update state
    // emit deterministic event payload (tooling decodes off-chain)
}

Avoid building business logic that depends on off-chain event delivery.

Use qpi.tick() for deterministic time windows.

Examples:
- Cooldown: if (qpi.tick() < state.lastActionTick + COOLDOWN_TICKS) return;
- Expiry: if (qpi.tick() > order.expiryTick) cancel order;
- Voting deadlines: proposal.deadline = qpi.tick() + VOTING_TICKS;

Guidance:
- Never use wall-clock time in contract logic.
- Keep windows large enough for network latency and user UX.
- Validate additions for overflow when using very large constants.

